WEBVTT

00:22.280 --> 00:23.360
CHAPTER VIII

00:24.180 --> 00:28.520
We passed a few sad hours until eleven o'clock, when the trial was to commence.

00:28.520 --> 00:34.540
My father and the rest of the family being obliged to attend as witnesses, I accompanied them to the court.

00:35.480 --> 00:39.580
During the whole of this wretched mockery of justice, I suffered living torture.

00:40.400 --> 00:47.700
It was to be decided whether the result of my curiosity and lawless devices would cause the death of two of my fellow beings,

00:48.160 --> 00:53.800
one a smiling babe full of innocence and joy, the other far more dreadfully murdered,

00:53.800 --> 00:59.220
with every aggravation of infamy that could make the murder memorable in horror.

01:00.800 --> 01:05.520
Justine also was a girl of merit and possessed qualities which promised to render her life happy.

01:06.120 --> 01:12.140
Now all was to be obliterated in an ignominious grave, and I the cause.

01:13.040 --> 01:18.140
A thousand times rather would I have confessed myself guilty of the crime ascribed to Justine,

01:18.140 --> 01:24.540
but I was absent when it was committed, and such a declaration would have been considered as the ravings of a madman,

01:24.660 --> 01:27.640
and would not have exculpated her who suffered through me.

01:30.040 --> 01:36.420
The appearance of Justine was calm. She was dressed in mourning, and her countenance, always engaging,

01:37.000 --> 01:40.680
was rendered by the solemnity of her feelings exquisitely beautiful.

01:40.680 --> 01:47.680
Yet she appeared confident in innocence and did not tremble, although gazed on and execrated by thousands,

01:48.100 --> 01:53.380
for all the kindness which her beauty might otherwise have excited was obliterated in the minds of the spectators

01:53.380 --> 01:57.060
by the imagination of the enormity she was supposed to have committed.

01:58.340 --> 02:02.060
She was tranquil, yet her tranquillity was evidently constrained,

02:02.620 --> 02:06.860
and as her confusion had before her been adduced as proof of her guilt,

02:07.740 --> 02:10.280
she worked up in her mind to an appearance of courage.

02:11.360 --> 02:16.320
When she entered the court, she threw her eyes round it, and quickly discovered where we were seated.

02:17.440 --> 02:21.840
A tear seemed to dim her eye when she saw us, but she quickly recovered herself,

02:22.280 --> 02:26.000
and a look of sorrowful affection seemed to attest her utter guiltlessness.

02:27.280 --> 02:33.640
The trial began, and after the advocate against her had stated the charge, several witnesses were called.

02:34.580 --> 02:41.360
Several strange facts combined against her, which might have staggered anyone who had not such proof of her innocence as I had.

02:42.260 --> 02:45.720
She had been out the whole of the night on which the murder had been committed,

02:46.120 --> 02:50.160
and towards morning had been perceived by a market woman not far from the spot

02:50.160 --> 02:52.980
where the body of the murdered child had been afterwards found.

02:53.500 --> 02:57.480
The woman asked her what she did there, but she looked very strangely,

02:57.960 --> 03:01.000
and only returned a confused and unintelligible answer.

03:01.860 --> 03:06.960
She returned to the house about eight o'clock, and when one inquired where she had passed the night,

03:07.460 --> 03:13.180
she replied that she had been looking for the child and demanded earnestly if anything had been heard concerning him.

03:14.120 --> 03:18.920
When shown the body, she fell into violent hysterics and kept her bed for several days.

03:19.440 --> 03:23.660
The picture was then produced, which the servant had found in her pocket,

03:24.300 --> 03:31.240
and when Elizabeth, in a faltering voice, proved that it was the same which an hour before the child had been missed

03:31.240 --> 03:36.940
she had placed around his neck, a murmur of horror and indignation filled the court.

03:39.020 --> 03:40.820
Justine was called on for her defence.

03:41.860 --> 03:45.060
As the trial had proceeded, her countenance had halted.

03:46.160 --> 03:50.040
Surprise, horror and misery were strongly expressed.

03:51.140 --> 03:55.240
Sometimes she struggled with her tears, but when she was desired to plead,

03:55.820 --> 04:00.160
she collected her powers and spoke in an audible, though variable voice.

04:29.760 --> 04:33.280
She then related that by the permission of Elizabeth,

04:33.720 --> 04:37.080
she had passed the evening of the night on which the murder had been committed

04:37.080 --> 04:41.780
at the house of an aunt at Shen, a village situated about a league from Geneva.

04:42.780 --> 04:45.040
On her return at about nine o'clock, she said that she had been looking for the child,

04:45.040 --> 04:49.200
She met a man who asked her if she had seen anything of the child who was lost.

04:50.180 --> 04:53.660
She was alarmed by this account and passed several hours in looking for him

04:53.660 --> 04:58.580
when the gates of Geneva were shut and she was forced to remain several hours of the night in her barn

04:58.580 --> 05:03.520
belonging to a cottage, being unwilling to call up the inhabitants to whom she was well known.

05:04.680 --> 05:06.520
Most of the night she spent here watching.

05:07.180 --> 05:09.840
Towards morning she believed that she slept for a few minutes.

05:10.360 --> 05:12.720
Some steps disturbed her and she awoke.

05:12.720 --> 05:18.260
It was dawn and she quitted her asylum that she might again endeavour to find my brother.

05:19.420 --> 05:23.660
If she had gone near the spot where his body lay, it was without her knowledge.

05:24.720 --> 05:28.340
That she had been bewildered when questioned by the market woman was not surprising

05:28.340 --> 05:33.120
since she had passed a sleepless night and the fate of poor William was yet uncertain.

05:34.400 --> 05:37.020
Concerning the picture, she could give no account.

05:38.320 --> 05:41.680
I know, continued the unhappy victim,

05:42.320 --> 05:46.240
how heavily and fatally this one circumstance weighs against me.

05:46.700 --> 05:51.160
But I have no power of explaining it, and when I have expressed my utter ignorance

05:51.160 --> 05:56.640
I am only left to conjecture concerning the probabilities by which it might have been placed in my pocket.

05:57.580 --> 06:01.760
But here also I am checked. I believe that I have no enemy on earth

06:01.760 --> 06:05.640
and none surely would have been so wicked as to destroy me wantonly.

06:05.640 --> 06:12.020
Did the murderer place it there? I know of no opportunity afforded him for so doing.

06:12.640 --> 06:17.740
Or, if I had, why should he have stolen the jewel to part with it again so soon?

06:19.440 --> 06:24.940
I commit my cause to the justice of my judges, yet I see no room for hope.

06:25.720 --> 06:29.820
I beg permission to have a few witnesses examined concerning my character

06:29.820 --> 06:35.320
and if their testimony shall not overweigh my supposed guilt, I must be condemned.

06:35.320 --> 06:38.740
Although I would pledge my salvation on my innocence.

06:41.860 --> 06:46.660
Several witnesses were called who had known her for many years, and they spoke well of her.

06:47.000 --> 06:50.180
But fear and hatred of the crime of which they supposed her guilty

06:50.180 --> 06:52.720
rendered them timorous and unwilling to come forward.

06:55.000 --> 06:59.960
Elizabeth saw even this last resource, her excellent dispositions and irreproachable conduct

06:59.960 --> 07:04.320
about to fail the accused, when, although violently agitated,

07:04.320 --> 07:06.880
she desired permission to address the court.

07:08.240 --> 07:14.780
I am, said she, the cousin of the unhappy child who was murdered, or rather his sister,

07:15.140 --> 07:20.820
for I was educated by and have lived with his parents ever since and even long before his birth.

07:21.760 --> 07:25.740
It may therefore be judged indecent in me to come forward on this occasion,

07:26.160 --> 07:31.360
but when I see a fellow creature about to perish to the cowardice of her pretended friends,

07:31.360 --> 07:36.180
I wish to be allowed to speak that I may say what I know of her character.

07:37.300 --> 07:39.140
I am well acquainted with the accused.

07:39.940 --> 07:45.820
I have lived in the same house with her at one time for five and at another for nearly two years.

07:46.620 --> 07:52.340
During all that period she appeared to me the most amiable and benevolent of human creatures.

07:53.040 --> 07:58.680
She nursed Madame Frankenstein, my aunt, in her last illness with the greatest affection and care,

07:58.680 --> 08:06.600
and afterwards attended her own mother during a tedious illness in a manner that excited the admiration of all who knew her,

08:06.860 --> 08:11.600
after which she again lived in my uncle's house where she was beloved by all the family.

08:12.240 --> 08:18.040
She was warmly attached to the child who is now dead and acted towards him like a most affectionate mother.

08:18.840 --> 08:25.020
For my own part I do not hesitate to say that notwithstanding all the evidence produced against her,

08:25.220 --> 08:28.020
I believe and rely on her perfect innocence.

08:28.680 --> 08:31.260
She had no temptation for such an action.

08:32.020 --> 08:37.180
As to the bauble on which the chief proof rests, if she had so earnestly desired it,

08:37.360 --> 08:41.480
I should have willingly given it to her. So much do I esteem and value her.

08:43.460 --> 08:47.480
A murmur of approbation followed Elizabeth's simple and powerful appeal,

08:48.040 --> 08:52.800
but it was excited by her generous interference and not in favour of poor Justine,

08:52.800 --> 08:58.820
on whom the public indignation was turned with renewed violence, charging her with the blackest ingratitude.

09:00.100 --> 09:03.740
She herself wept as Elizabeth spoke, but she did not answer.

09:05.020 --> 09:08.760
My own agitation and anguish was extreme during the whole trial.

09:09.500 --> 09:12.080
I believed in her innocence. I knew it.

09:12.620 --> 09:15.620
Could the demon who had, I did not a minute doubt,

09:16.040 --> 09:20.860
murdered my brother also in his hellish sport have betrayed the innocent to death in ignominy?

09:20.860 --> 09:24.300
I could not sustain the horror of my situation,

09:24.740 --> 09:31.260
and when I perceived that the popular voice and the countenances of the judge had already condemned my unhappy victim,

09:31.860 --> 09:33.740
I rushed out of the court in agony.

09:34.620 --> 09:37.320
The tortures of the accused did not equal mine.

09:38.120 --> 09:44.240
She was sustained by innocence, but the fangs of remorse tore my bosom and would not forgo their hold.

09:46.580 --> 09:49.100
I passed a night of unmingled wretchedness.

09:49.100 --> 09:54.740
In the morning I went to the court. My lips and throat were parched.

09:55.620 --> 10:01.280
I dared not ask the fatal question, but I was known, and the officer guessed the cause of my visit.

10:01.960 --> 10:07.040
The ballots had been thrown. They were all black, and Justine was condemned.

10:08.720 --> 10:11.760
I cannot pretend to describe what I then felt.

10:12.960 --> 10:15.720
I had before experienced sensations of horror,

10:15.720 --> 10:19.260
and when I have endeavoured to bestow upon them adequate expressions,

10:20.480 --> 10:25.020
but words cannot convey an idea of the heart-sickening despair that I then endured.

10:26.060 --> 10:30.960
The person to whom I addressed myself added that Justine had already confessed her guilt.

10:32.080 --> 10:36.520
That evidence, he observed, was hardly required in so glaring a case,

10:36.680 --> 10:42.460
but I am glad of it, and indeed none of our judges like to condemn a criminal upon circumstantial evidence,

10:42.880 --> 10:43.880
be it ever so decisive.

10:43.880 --> 10:49.900
This was strange and unexpected intelligence. What could it mean?

10:50.760 --> 10:55.540
Had my eyes deceived me, and was I really as mad as the whole world would believe me to be

10:55.540 --> 10:57.940
if I disclosed the object of my suspicions?

10:58.660 --> 11:03.120
I hastened to return home, and Elizabeth eagerly demanded the result.

11:04.380 --> 11:09.340
My cousin, replied I, it is decided as you may have expected.

11:09.980 --> 11:15.420
All judges had rather that ten innocent should suffer than that one guilty should escape.

11:16.480 --> 11:17.800
But she has confessed.

11:25.280 --> 11:30.920
This was a dire blow to poor Elizabeth, who had relied with firmness upon Justine's innocence.

11:32.280 --> 11:36.020
Alas, said she, how shall I ever again believe in human goodness?

11:36.660 --> 11:42.700
Justine, whom I loved and esteemed as my sister, how could she put on those smiles of innocence only to betray?

11:43.520 --> 11:49.100
Her mild eyes seemed incapable of any severity or guile, and yet she has committed a murder.

11:51.060 --> 11:55.580
Soon after, we heard that the poor victim had expressed a desire to see my cousin.

11:56.560 --> 12:01.720
My father wished her not to go, but said that he left it to her own judgment and feelings to decide.

12:02.380 --> 12:08.960
Yes, said Elizabeth, I will go, although she is guilty, and you, Victor, shall accompany me.

12:09.480 --> 12:10.820
I cannot go alone.

12:12.520 --> 12:16.420
The idea of this visit was torture to me, yet I could not refuse.

12:17.600 --> 12:22.700
We entered the gloomy prison chamber and beheld Justine sitting on some straw at the farther end.

12:23.320 --> 12:26.700
Her hands were manacled, and her head rested on her knees.

12:27.280 --> 12:34.880
She rose on seeing us enter, and when we were left alone with her, she threw herself at the feet of Elizabeth, weeping bitterly.

12:35.640 --> 12:37.020
My cousin wept also.

12:38.240 --> 12:43.440
Oh, Justine, said she, why did you rob me of my last consolation?

12:43.760 --> 12:50.020
I relied on your innocence, and although I was then very wretched, I was not so miserable as I am now.

12:51.960 --> 12:55.180
And do you also believe that I am so very, very wicked?

12:55.180 --> 12:59.440
Do you also join with my enemies to crush me, to condemn me as a murderer?

13:00.440 --> 13:03.040
Her voice was suffocated with sobs.

13:04.180 --> 13:06.040
Rise, my poor girl, said Elizabeth.

13:06.740 --> 13:08.580
Why do you kneel if you are innocent?

13:09.260 --> 13:10.760
I am not one of your enemies.

13:11.180 --> 13:17.500
I believed you guiltless, notwithstanding every evidence, until I heard that you had yourself declared your guilt.

13:18.340 --> 13:20.140
That report, you say, is false.

13:20.140 --> 13:26.960
And be assured, dear Justine, that nothing can shake my confidence in you for a moment, but your own confession.

13:28.160 --> 13:31.280
I did confess, but I confessed a lie.

13:32.220 --> 13:39.580
I confessed that I might obtain absolution, but now that falsehood lies heavier at my heart than all my other sins.

13:40.320 --> 13:41.980
The God of heaven forgive me.

13:42.680 --> 13:46.040
Ever since I was condemned, my confessor has besieged me.

13:46.040 --> 13:51.120
He threatened and menaced until I almost began to think that I was the monster that he said I was.

13:51.940 --> 13:57.020
He threatened excommunication and hellfire in my last moments if I continued obdurate.

13:57.900 --> 14:00.240
Dear lady, I had none to support me.

14:00.720 --> 14:04.460
All looked on me as a wretch doomed to ignominy and perdition.

14:05.100 --> 14:06.160
What could I do?

14:06.740 --> 14:11.980
In an evil hour I subscribed to a lie, and now only am I truly miserable.

14:13.080 --> 14:14.880
She paused, weeping.

14:14.880 --> 14:16.640
And then continued.

14:17.880 --> 14:25.540
I thought with horror, my sweet lady, that you should believe your Justine, whom your blessed aunt had so highly honored and whom you loved,

14:26.040 --> 14:30.740
was a creature capable of a crime which none but the devil himself could have perpetrated.

14:31.480 --> 14:38.980
Dear William, dearest blessed child, I soon shall see you again in heaven, where we shall all be happy.

14:39.520 --> 14:44.040
And that consoles me, going as I am to suffer ignominy and death.

14:46.240 --> 14:50.860
Oh, Justine, forgive me for having for one moment distrusted you.

14:51.260 --> 14:52.540
Why did you confess?

14:53.580 --> 14:55.820
But do not mourn, dear girl, do not fear.

14:56.640 --> 15:03.700
I will proclaim, I will prove your innocence, I will melt the stony hearts of your enemies by the tears and prayers.

15:04.420 --> 15:05.500
You shall not die.

15:06.000 --> 15:10.840
You, my playfellow, my companion, my sister, perish on the scaffold?

15:10.840 --> 15:14.840
No, I could never survive so horrible a misfortune.

15:18.800 --> 15:20.300
Justine shook her head mournfully.

15:21.180 --> 15:23.380
I do not fear to die, she said.

15:24.160 --> 15:25.280
That pang is past.

15:26.180 --> 15:29.500
God raises my weakness and gives me courage to endure the worst.

15:30.280 --> 15:39.140
I leave a sad and bitter world, and if you remember me and think of me as of one unjustly condemned, I am resigned to the fate awaiting me.

15:39.140 --> 15:43.280
Learn from me, dear lady, to submit impatience to the will of heaven.

15:46.440 --> 15:53.860
During this conversation, I had retired to a corner of the prison room, where I could conceal the horrid anguish that possessed me.

15:54.500 --> 15:56.700
Despair? Who dared talk of that?

15:57.500 --> 16:05.620
The poor victim, who on the morrow was to pass the awful boundary between life and death, felt not, as I did, such deep and bitter agony.

16:06.600 --> 16:12.580
I gnashed my teeth and ground them together, uttering a groan that came from my inmost soul.

16:14.080 --> 16:14.840
Justine started.

16:16.080 --> 16:18.480
When she saw who it was, she approached me and said,

16:18.880 --> 16:21.500
Dear sir, you are very kind to visit you.

16:22.560 --> 16:25.220
I do hope you do not believe that I am guilty.

16:27.160 --> 16:28.560
I could not answer.

16:29.380 --> 16:30.900
No, Justine, said Elizabeth.

16:30.900 --> 16:37.500
He is more convinced of your innocence than I was, for even when he heard that you had confessed, he did not credit it.

16:38.760 --> 16:40.080
I truly thank him.

16:40.540 --> 16:46.100
In these last moments, I feel the sincerest gratitude towards those who think of me with kindness.

16:47.120 --> 16:50.480
How sweet is the affection of others to such a wretch as I am.

16:50.980 --> 17:00.500
It removes more than half my misfortune, and I feel as if I could die in peace now that my innocence is acknowledged by you, dear lady, and your cousin.

17:03.420 --> 17:07.360
Thus the poor sufferer tried to comfort others and herself.

17:08.440 --> 17:11.260
She indeed gained the resignation she desired.

17:12.280 --> 17:20.050
But I, the true murderer, felt the never-dying worm alive in my bosom, which allowed of no hope or consolation.

17:21.560 --> 17:26.380
Elizabeth also wept and was unhappy, but hers also was the misery of innocence,

17:26.380 --> 17:32.920
which, like a cloud that passes over the fair moon, for a while hides but cannot tarnish its brightness.

17:34.400 --> 17:37.620
Anguish and despair had penetrated into the core of my heart.

17:38.280 --> 17:41.720
I bore a hell within me which nothing could extinguish.

17:42.580 --> 17:48.420
We stayed several hours with Justine, and it was with great difficulty that Elizabeth could tear herself away.

17:48.780 --> 17:52.400
I wish, cried she, that I were to die with you.

17:52.720 --> 17:54.780
I cannot live in this world of misery.

17:57.140 --> 18:02.660
Justine assumed an air of cheerfulness, while she with difficulty repressed her bitter tears.

18:03.540 --> 18:07.260
She embraced Elizabeth and said in a voice of half-suppressed emotion,

18:08.060 --> 18:12.620
Farewell, sweet lady, dearest Elizabeth, my beloved and only friend.

18:13.600 --> 18:17.540
May heaven, in its bounty, bless and preserve you.

18:17.860 --> 18:20.720
May this be the last misfortune that you will ever suffer.

18:21.420 --> 18:24.500
Live and be happy, and make others so.

18:27.360 --> 18:30.460
And on the morrow, Justine died.

18:32.160 --> 18:38.740
Elizabeth's heart-rending eloquence failed to move the judges from their settled conviction in the criminality of the saintly sufferer.

18:39.880 --> 18:43.300
My passionate and indignant appeals were lost upon them,

18:43.680 --> 18:49.100
and when I received their cold answers and heard the harsh, unfeeling reasoning of these men,

18:49.620 --> 18:51.920
my purposed avowal died away on my lips.

18:51.920 --> 18:58.560
Thus I might proclaim myself a madman, but not revoke the sentence passed upon my wretched victim.

18:59.800 --> 19:02.460
She perished on the scaffold as a murderess.

19:04.660 --> 19:10.360
From the tortures of my own heart, I turned to contemplate the deep and voiceless grief of my Elizabeth.

19:11.320 --> 19:17.520
This also was my doing, and my father's woe and the desolation of that late so smiling home

19:17.520 --> 19:20.700
all was the work of my thrice accursed hands.

19:20.700 --> 19:25.280
Ye weep, unhappy ones, but these are not your last tears.

19:26.120 --> 19:32.360
Again shall you rise the funeral wail, and the sound of your lamentations shall again and again be heard.

19:33.300 --> 19:37.440
Frankenstein, your son, your kinsman, your early much-loved friend,

19:38.180 --> 19:41.520
he who would spend each vital drop of blood for your sakes,

19:41.800 --> 19:46.840
who has no thought nor sense of joy, except as it is mirrored also in your dear countenances,

19:46.840 --> 19:51.500
who would fill the air with blessings and spend his life in serving you,

19:52.120 --> 19:54.920
he bids you weep, to shed countless tears,

19:56.260 --> 20:00.040
happy beyond his hopes if thus inexorable fate be satisfied,

20:00.620 --> 20:06.240
and if the destruction pours before the peace of the grave have succeeded to your sad torments.

20:07.620 --> 20:13.360
Thus spoke my prophetic soul, as, torn by remorse, horror and despair,

20:13.360 --> 20:19.020
I beheld those I loved spend vain sorrow upon the graves of William and Justine,

20:19.480 --> 20:22.500
the first hapless victims to my unhallowed arts.

